The Independent Policing Oversight Authority has directed police officers to use non-violent means in enforcing the curfew order. Ipoa chairperson Anne Makori said on Saturday that ant fatalities and injuries sustained by citizens during the curfew implementation should be reported to the authority. “Police shall first use non-violent means. Force shall be proportionate. Death, serious injuries shall be reported immediately to Ipoa,” Makori said. She added, “Ipoa has put in place strategies to ensure that police accountability during the cause of the journey." She has asked Inspector General of Police Hillary Mutyambai to ensure the officers enforce the directive in compliance with the law. “The IG of Police to bring to the attention of all the operation commanders that public order management behooves the police to conduct themselves professionally and within the confines of the law,” she said. Makori has also asked the public to comply with the curfew hours in order to avoid being forced by the police. The police officers are in the limelight following the brutal implementation of the curfew order given by President Uhuru Kenyatta. Chaos were witnessed at the Likoni crossing channel as early as 4:30pm. The dusk-to-dawn order began on Friday evening to contain spread of the coronavirus. Edited by R.Wamochie